we have "roofed forest" and imo this is a good term
They're called dark forests as of 1.13, and the names are for totally different reasons (canopies versus the tops of caves) so I don't see why this precedent should be followed.
Then ceilinged, hasCeiling doesn't match the naming style really
hasCeiling is just fine and sounds a lot better than ceilinged.
How about skyObstructed
I'm in favor of hasCeiling. Typically you talk about the ceiling of a cave rather than its roof and ceilinged is simply wrong.

hasCeiling is a wrong term. Had you use hasCeiling for a field in a pojo, spring framework or so will generate accessors like isHasCeiling which shows hasCeiling makes no sense for a name of a boolean field. Boolean field names should be adjective or adjective phrases, not verb phrases.
There is nothing wrong with hasCeiling here, both is and has are okay prefixes for booleans. How does spring have anything to do with this?

liach, I'm sure we've had this discussion about prefixing boolean fields with "has" before. The yarn style guide advises against verb phrases in fields, but it's only a guide, and especially when the alternative sounds like broken English, "has..." works fine for boolean fields. As an English speaker "has..." feels a bit like an adjective phrase anyway, even if it grammatically isn't - it specifies an attribute of the object.
This probably is fine since there is hasSkylight
GeneratorOptions$WorldGeneratorType. The name is too obtuse, needs to be optimized
How is level type different from world generator type etc?

We spent like half an hour deciding what to name these three classes. This is called LevelType, because it maps directly to the level-type field in server.properties. MapType is called that because that's the localization string of the button that controls that setting (although it was still unclear to us how that button showed options that are not in the MapType enum but are in LevelType like Large Biomes. WorldGeneratorType is used in the buffet generator. Maybe BuffetWorldGeneratorType is actually a better name for that one.
That client button appears to me as a fancy layer above the actual level type (this boi) that is used in actual save. Mojang does offer some sort of shortcut for powerful maneuvers on client
Seriously, ServerWorldProperties, don't sneak in your trashy names

problem is that now we have WorldProperties and LevelProperties describing the same construct. The impl of levelproperties is a big mess of interfaces like World, except iirc most of them aren't used anywhere.
Context is important!
I'd say this specific category may work better in a specific pr we can bikeshed
WorldProperties is the properties of a world, LevelProperties is level.dat and is both a WorldProperties and a SaveProperties. Simple as that.

@i509VCB I've opened #1337 for debate, yet no one comes and just explains in this comment thread. I am pretty sure I've asked people to look into my debate issue yet no one seems to care yet, so 🤷 cannot do anything
